# History

Reuse what you already typed. The interactive keys are near-universal; `!`
history expansion is a bash/zsh feature (fish and nu use search instead). Pair
with @shell/fzf to turn reverse-search into a fuzzy picker.

## Interactive recall â€” every shell

| Key | Does |
|-----|------|
| `Ctrl-R` | incremental reverse search; press again for older matches |
| `Ctrl-S` | forward search (often needs `stty -ixon` to free the key) |
| `Up` / `Ctrl-P` | previous command |
| `Alt-.` / `Esc .` | insert last argument of previous command (repeat to cycle) |
| `Ctrl-G` | abort the search, keep the line |

`Alt-.` is the quiet hero: `mkdir foo` then `cd <Alt-.>` pulls `foo` in.

## History expansion â€” bash / zsh

The `!` event designators expand *before* the command runs.

| Form | Expands to |
|------|-----------|
| `!!` | the entire last command |
| `!$` | last argument of the last command |
| `!*` | all arguments of the last command |
| `!^` | first argument |
| `!n` / `!-2` | command number `n` / two back |
| `!foo` | most recent command starting with `foo` |
| `!?foo?` | most recent command *containing* `foo` |
| `^old^new` | re-run last command, replacing `old` with `new` |

```bash
apt install ngix      # typo
^ngix^nginx           # re-runs as: apt install nginx
sudo !!               # re-run the last command under sudo
```

Add `:p` (`!!:p`) to *print* the expansion without running it â€” a safety check
before `sudo !!`.

## fish and nu

- **fish**: type a prefix then `Up` for prefix-search; `Ctrl-R` opens an
  interactive history pager. No `!!` â€” use `Alt-.` and search instead.
- **nu**: `Ctrl-R` fuzzy-searches history; history is a SQLite-backed table you
  can query with `history | where command =~ 'git'`.

## Tuning recall quality

| Shell | Knob |
|-------|------|
| bash | `HISTCONTROL=ignoreboth`, `HISTSIZE`, `shopt -s histappend` |
| zsh | `setopt hist_ignore_all_dups share_history inc_append_history` |
| fish | dedup is automatic; `history merge` syncs sessions |
| nu | `$env.config.history.max_size`; `file_format = "sqlite"` |
